# ADR (Architecture Decision Record) Rule

## When to Create an ADR Stub

Create a stub in `docs/adr/` when:
- Adding a new npm/pip package that will be a core dependency
- Choosing between two viable architectural approaches
- Introducing a new pattern that ALL future code should follow
- Making a breaking schema or API change
- Choosing a new service, provider, or infrastructure component

## How to Create a Stub (AI Task)

1. Find the next ADR number: `ls docs/adr/ | sort | tail -1`
2. Create `docs/adr/ADR-{NNN}-{kebab-case-title}.md`
3. Fill in **Context** and **Options Considered** only — AI is permitted to write these.
4. Leave **Decision**, **Rationale**, and **Consequences** as `<!-- HUMAN-AUTHORED -->` blocks.
5. Set Status to `Proposed`.

## What AI Must NEVER Do

- Never fill in `## Decision`, `## Rationale`, or `## Consequences` sections.
- Never set Status to `Accepted` — only humans do that.
- Never modify an ADR that already has Status `Accepted` — these are immutable.

## After Creating a Stub

- Add an entry to `DECISIONS.md` referencing the ADR file.
- Notify the human: "ADR stub created — please fill in the Decision section before merging."

## ADR Stub Template

```markdown
---
Status: Proposed
Date: YYYY-MM-DD
---

# ADR-{NNN}: {Title}

## Status
Proposed

## Context
[AI writes: why this decision is needed, what forces are in play]

## Options Considered
| Option | Pros | Cons |
|--------|------|------|

## Decision
<!-- HUMAN-AUTHORED -->

## Rationale
<!-- HUMAN-AUTHORED -->

## Consequences
<!-- HUMAN-AUTHORED -->
```
